'''Charles Darwin''' d [[amezruy agaman|amusnaw n umezruy agaman]], d [[amesnakal]]<ref>Desmond, Adrian; Moore, James; Browne, Janet (2004). Oxford Dictionary of National Biography. Oxford, England: Oxford University Press. doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/7176.</ref> [[Tagelda Yeddukklen|Abṛitan]] ilul g [[Anegliz|tmurt n Unegliz]] deg wass n [[12 fuṛaṛ]] [[1809]] di [[Shrewsbury]]. Yukkes (yemmut) deg wass n [[19 yebrir]] [[1882]]. Yekker-d deg twacult tussnant anda baba-s d [[Robert Darwin]] yella d [[amessuji]] ma d dadda-s (jeddi-s) [[Erasmus Darwin]] yella  d [[amessengam]] yakk d amaskar, Charles Darwin yell-d (ikeseb-d) tamusni-ynes s wesnulfu n [[Tamhazt|teẓri n temhazt]] i d-yeqqaren d akken yakk [[Amuddir|imuddiren]] i d-yellan deg teɣzi n umezruy kkant-d yakk seg [[aẓaṛ imezdi|yiwen n uẓar]],<ref>{{amnir n wedlis|amaskar=Coyne, Jerry A. |azwel=Why Evolution is True|anefsar=Viking|aseggas=2009 |tasniwin=8–11|uṭṭun ameslugen=978-0-670-02053-9}}</ref>. Akken i d-issumer tiẓri i d-yeqqaren d akken inawen-a yebṭan s [[tamhazt|temhazt]] mmugen-d s usrag (ssebba) n yiwet n temhalt umi yessemma '''[[afran agaman]]'''. Imenɣi i lmend n weslak daɣen ila (yesɛa) yiwen n usemdu n wefran amguran yettekkayen deg [[amyaraw|umyaraw]] ufrin n imuddiren.<ref name="Larson79-111">{{Tanagit n Harvard war tacciwin|Larson|2004| pp=79–111}}</ref>. S wannay n imuddiren, Darwin yegra-d tazrawt i wesmuti (abeddel) i d-yettilin deg imuddiren sɣur n [[tadermist|tdermisin]]. Deg useggas [[1838]] yessnefli tiẓri-ynes (afran agaman) yettwassnen acku yeẓṛa d acu i d uguren id tezmer ad teglu yissen tiẓri ayyi aladɣa deg wammas n [[ajjed|yimasɣanen]]. ɣef wanect-a i yeǧǧa tiẓri-ynes d tuffirt deg tazwara ifesr-it gar n wayyawen-is kan. Deg wakud anda iy ssemd tigmayin-is (ikemmel inadiyen-is) i wakken ad iheggi tiririyin ɣef tsentilin i yettṛaǧu af teẓri-ynes. Deg useggas n [[1858]] yewweṭ-as-d isali i Darwin d akken yiwen n wergaz isem-is [[Alfred Russel Wallace]] ixeddem ɣef yiwet n teẓri yemmugen am teẓri-ynes ayen yeǧǧan Darwin ad yefser igemmad n tegmayin-is imir-nni yakan<br/>
Darwin yettumeggez d [[asnudran]] yettwassnen yakk, Dɣa yesseker-d aṭas n yidlisen deg tɣult n [[tasnudert|tesnudert]] d acu kan tiẓri ayyi tegla-d s waṭas n yizɣanen aladɣa deg tlemmast n imasɣanen (imrabṭen n ddin) deg umadal yakk<br/>.
Deg wayen umi yessemma [[Assaɣ imezli (tamhazt)|assaɣ imezli]], Darwin yeqqim deg uɣilif i wakken ad yaf assaɣ-a iy teqqnen kar n wemdan atrar d [[ibki|yebka]], deg useggas n [[1859]] efser tiẓri n temhazt s yinzaten uzmiren (ijehden) deg wedlis n [[Iẓuran n telmas|aẓaṛ n telmas]] ayen id t-iǧǧan ad yerna (ad yeɣleb) tugit i d-immuger deg wammas n tmetti tussnant ɣef tiẓri ayyi.<ref>{{amnir n wedlis |azwel=Why Evolution is True |aneggar = Coyne |amezwar=Jerry A. |assaɣ n umaskar=Jerry Coyne |aseggas=2009 |anefsar=[[Oxford University Press]] |adeg= Oxford |Uṭṭun ameslugen=0-19-923084-6 |tasma=17 |Tabdert=In ''The Origin'', Darwin provided an alternative hypothesis for the development, diversification, and design of life. Much of that book presents evidence that not only supports evolution but at the same time refutes creationism. In Darwin's day, the evidence for his theories was compelling but not completely decisive.}}</ref><ref>{{amnir n wedlis |azwel=Forerunners of Darwin |aneggar=Glass |amezwar=Bentley |assaɣ n umaskar=Bentley Glass |aseggas=1959 |anefsar=Johns Hopkins University Press |adeg=Baltimore, MD |Uṭṭun ameslugen= 0-8018-0222-9|tasna=iv |tabdert=Darwin's solution is a magnificent synthesis of evidence...a synthesis...compelling in honesty and comprehensiveness}}</ref>. Timetti tussnant d tin yeddgen (iqeblen) tiẓri n temhazt d tin yellan s tidet deg useggas n [[1870]] maca aṭas deg-sen llan d wid iy smenyifiyen issegza niden alammi i d-telfa '''tuddsa tanamhazt tatrart''' ([[1930 - [[1950]]) anda i d-yella umtawa meqqren d akken taɣlelt tagamant tella d amsedday agejdan i temhazt.<ref name=JvW>{{Tanagit s Harvard war tacciwin|van Wyhe|2008}}</ref><ref name=b3847>{{Tanagit s Harvard war tacciwin|Bowler|2003|pp=178–179, 338, 347}}</ref>. S tsileɣt niden, Asnirem ussnan n Darwin tga d tiẓri tameslugant i tussniwin tisnudranin yakk akken i d-tessegzay i tugta yellan deg-s.<ref>[http://darwin-online.org.uk/biography.html The Complete Works of Darwin Online – Biography.] ''darwin-online.org.uk''. Retrieved 2006-12-15<br />{{Taganit s Harvard war tacciwin|Dobzhansky|1973}} {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221233249/http://darwin-online.org.uk/biography.html |date=21 fuṛaṛ 2018}}</ref><ref>As Darwinian scholar Joseph Carroll of the University of Missouri–St. Louis puts it in his introduction to a modern reprint of Darwin's work: "''The Origin of Species'' has special claims on our attention. It is one of the two or three most significant works of all time—one of those works that fundamentally and permanently alter our vision of the world...It is argued with a singularly rigorous consistency but it is also eloquent, imaginatively evocative, and rhetorically compelling." {{Amnir n wedlis |azwel=On the origin of species by means of natural selection |amara=Carroll, Joseph |aseggas=2003 |anefsar=Broadview |adeg= Peterborough, Ontario|uṭṭun ameslugen= 1-55111-337-6|tasma=15 |akala=}}</ref>

